{{ template "chart.description" . }}

This [Helm chart](https://helm.sh/) deploys [tik](https://github.com/metio/tik): the read-only board / EDN API (`tik serve`) and, optionally, a mail ingester that turns inbound email into signed events. See the [Values](#values) section below for every option.

The chart is published in OCI format and can be downloaded from `oci://ghcr.io/metio/helm-charts/tik` using `helm`.

Install it with:

```shell
helm install SOME_RELEASE oci://ghcr.io/metio/helm-charts/tik --version SOME_VERSION
```

Replace `SOME_RELEASE` and `SOME_VERSION` with appropriate values for your environment. In general, we recommend running the latest available version.

## Deployment modes

Set `mode` to choose how tik runs:

- **`backend`** (the default, and the simple one) ŌĆö a single `tik backend`
  supervisor process runs everything you declare in `backend.config` (a
  `pipelines.edn`) as one delegated agent: the board, mail ingestion, recurring
  tickets, dashboards, effects. **One Deployment, one config.** A pipeline is
  either continuous (`:watch true` ŌĆö `serve`, `bridge imap --watch`, each
  restarted on exit) or scheduled (a verb fired on an `:every` ISO-8601
  interval ŌĆö `recur`/`probe`/`bridge pop3`/`effects`). Because it acts by
  producing ordinary signed, content-addressed events, and `recur` is
  idempotent, it needs no leader ŌĆö a missed fire self-heals.

  ```yaml
  mode: backend
  backend:
    signingKeySecret: { name: tik-signing-key }   # so it can sign events it writes
    config: |
      {:pipelines
       [{:id :board :watch true :run ["serve" "--port" "7777"]}
        {:id :mail  :watch true :run ["bridge" "imap" "--watch" "--config" "/etc/tik/mail.edn"] :as "tik-backend"}
        {:id :release :every "PT1H" :run ["recur" "release-train"] :period :iso-week :as "tik-backend"}]}
    files:
      mail.edn: |
        {:imap {:host "imap.example.com" :user "desk@example.com"
                :password {:file "/etc/tik-secrets/mailbox-password"}}
         :process :support :default-actor "inbound"}
    passwordSecret: { name: tik-mailbox-password }   # mounted at /etc/tik-secrets
  ```

- **`split`** ŌĆö the board (`tik serve`) runs as its own **horizontally
  scalable** Deployment and mail ingestion as a separate workload. Choose this
  only when you need to scale the read board across nodes (which also needs a
  `ReadWriteMany` store). See the ingestion and scaling notes below.

Both modes serve the same read-only board ŌĆö `/` (live board), `/tickets.edn`, and `/explain/<id>.edn` ŌĆö fronted by a ClusterIP `Service`; expose it with your own Ingress or Gateway. The **store** is an append-only directory of signed, content-addressed events on a `PersistentVolumeClaim` at `/var/lib/tik` (`TIK_ROOT`) ŌĆö the one piece of durable state.

## The store and horizontal scaling

tik reads are derived-on-read and coordination-free, so the board itself scales without limit. The constraint is the shared store: with the default `persistence.accessModes: [ReadWriteOnce]` the volume binds to a single node, so the board (and the ingester, if enabled) must run there. That is the safe default and it co-locates automatically.

To scale the board across nodes, give the store an access mode that many nodes can mount:

```yaml
persistence:
  accessModes:
    - ReadWriteMany
replicas:
  min: 2
  max: 6   # a HorizontalPodAutoscaler owns the count from min upward
```

## Mail ingestion

Turn inbound email into signed events with `ingest.enabled: true`. The ingester reuses the same loop-safe, idempotent, DKIM-gated pipeline as the CLI: our own returned mail is dropped, auto-replies and bounces are recorded but never answered, and re-fetching a message is a no-op.

The protocol decides how it runs:

- `ingest.protocol: imap` ŌĆö a single-replica `Deployment` that holds the connection open with IMAP IDLE and ingests the instant mail arrives.
- `ingest.protocol: pop3` ŌĆö a `CronJob` (POP3 has no push) polling on `ingest.schedule`.

The ingester writes the store, so it needs a signing key, and it reads a config you supply:

```yaml
ingest:
  enabled: true
  protocol: imap
  # imap.edn / pop3.edn, rendered into a ConfigMap and passed via --config.
  # Reference the mailbox password as a {:file ŌĆ”} spec pointing at the mounted
  # Secret below ŌĆö never inline it here.
  config: |
    {:imap {:host "imap.example.com"
            :user "desk@example.com"
            :password {:file "/etc/tik/secrets/mailbox-password"}
            :mailbox "INBOX" :search "UNSEEN"}
     :process :support
     :default-actor "inbound"
     :dkim {:require true :authserv-id "mx.example.com"}}
  # a Secret with the Ed25519 signing key (mounted read-only; TIK_KEY points at it)
  signingKeySecret:
    name: tik-signing-key
    keyFile: id_ed25519
  # a Secret with the mailbox password, mounted at /etc/tik/secrets
  passwordSecret:
    name: tik-mailbox-password
```

Create the secrets out of band, e.g.:

```shell
kubectl create secret generic tik-signing-key --from-file=id_ed25519=/path/to/id_ed25519
kubectl create secret generic tik-mailbox-password --from-file=mailbox-password=/path/to/password
```

## NetworkPolicy

`networkPolicy.enabled: true` renders a board-scoped policy for your CNI ŌĆö pick `networkPolicy.engine`: `kubernetes` (the default `networking.k8s.io/v1`), `calico` (the aggregated `projectcalico.org/v3` API), or `cilium` (`cilium.io/v2`). Ingress to the board HTTP port is open by default (kubelet probes source from the node IP); scope it with `networkPolicy.http.from` or the native passthrough lists.

## Pod Security Standards

Every pod the chart renders is configured for **Pod Security Standards "restricted"**: `runAsNonRoot`, non-zero `runAsUser`/`runAsGroup`, `allowPrivilegeEscalation: false`, `readOnlyRootFilesystem: true`, `capabilities.drop: [ALL]`, `seccompProfile.type: RuntimeDefault`, and a pod-level `securityContext` that mirrors the strict posture. tik never calls the Kubernetes API, so no ServiceAccount token is mounted and no RBAC is granted.

## Uninstall

`helm uninstall` leaves the store `PersistentVolumeClaim` in place (Helm never deletes PVCs). Reclaim it with `kubectl delete pvc <release>-store -n <ns>` once you are sure the event log is no longer needed ŌĆö it is append-only history.

